events.description: The first temple to Venus, the Roman goddess of love, beauty and fertility, is dedicated by Quintus Fabius Maximus Gurges during the Third Samnite War.
events.html: • 295 BC – The first temple to Venus, the Roman goddess of love, beauty and fertility, is dedicated by Quintus Fabius Maximus Gurges during the Third Samnite War.[1]

events.description: Gaius Julius Caesar Octavianus, later known as Augustus, compels the Roman Senate to elect him Consul.
events.html: • 43 BC – Gaius Julius Caesar Octavianus, later known as Augustus, compels the Roman Senate to elect him Consul.

events.description: Abu Yazid, a Kharijite rebel leader, is defeated and killed in the Hodna Mountains in modern-day Algeria by Fatimid forces.
events.html: • 947 – Abu Yazid, a Kharijite rebel leader, is defeated and killed in the Hodna Mountains in modern-day Algeria by Fatimid forces.

events.description: Baldwin III of Jerusalem takes control of the Kingdom of Jerusalem from his mother Melisende, and also captures Ascalon.
events.html: • 1153 – Baldwin III of Jerusalem takes control of the Kingdom of Jerusalem from his mother Melisende, and also captures Ascalon.

events.description: Pope Pius II is elected the 211th Pope.
events.html: • 1458 – Pope Pius II is elected the 211th Pope.[2]

events.description: In Ireland, the Hiberno-Norman de Burghs (Burkes) and Cambro-Norman Fitzgeralds fight in the Battle of Knockdoe.
events.html: • 1504 – In Ireland, the Hiberno-Norman de Burghs (Burkes) and Cambro-Norman Fitzgeralds fight in the Battle of Knockdoe.[3]

events.description: Mary, Queen of Scots, aged 18, returns to Scotland after spending 13 years in France.
events.html: • 1561 – Mary, Queen of Scots, aged 18, returns to Scotland after spending 13 years in France.[4]

events.description: Eighty Years War: a besieging Dutch and English army led by Maurice of Orange forces the Spanish garrison of Sluis to capitulate.
events.html: • 1604 – Eighty Years War: a besieging Dutch and English army led by Maurice of Orange forces the Spanish garrison of Sluis to capitulate.[5]

events.description: The "Samlesbury witches", three women from the Lancashire village of Samlesbury, England, are put on trial, accused of practicing witchcraft, one of the most famous witch trials in British history.
events.html: • 1612 – The "Samlesbury witches", three women from the Lancashire village of Samlesbury, England, are put on trial, accused of practicing witchcraft, one of the most famous witch trials in British history.

events.description: Second Anglo-Dutch War: Rear Admiral Robert Holmes leads a raid on the Dutch island of Terschelling, destroying 150 merchant ships, an act later known as "Holmes's Bonfire".
events.html: • 1666 – Second Anglo-Dutch War: Rear Admiral Robert Holmes leads a raid on the Dutch island of Terschelling, destroying 150 merchant ships, an act later known as "Holmes's Bonfire".

events.description: Salem witch trials: In Salem, province of Massachusetts Bay, five people, one woman and four men, including a clergyman, are executed after being convicted of witchcraft.
events.html: • 1692 – Salem witch trials: In Salem, province of Massachusetts Bay, five people, one woman and four men, including a clergyman, are executed after being convicted of witchcraft.

events.description: Prince Charles Edward Stuart raises his standard in Glenfinnan: The start of the Second Jacobite Rebellion, known as "the 45".
events.html: • 1745 – Prince Charles Edward Stuart raises his standard in Glenfinnan: The start of the Second Jacobite Rebellion, known as "the 45".

events.description: Ottoman–Persian War: In the Battle of Kars, the Ottoman army is routed by Persian forces led by Nader Shah.
events.html: • 1745 – Ottoman–Persian War: In the Battle of Kars, the Ottoman army is routed by Persian forces led by Nader Shah.

events.description: Battle of Lagos: Naval battle during the Seven Years' War between Great Britain and France.
events.html: • 1759 – Battle of Lagos: Naval battle during the Seven Years' War between Great Britain and France.

events.description: Gustav III of Sweden stages a coup d'état, in which he assumes power and enacts a new constitution that divides power between the Riksdag and the King.
events.html: • 1772 – Gustav III of Sweden stages a coup d'état, in which he assumes power and enacts a new constitution that divides power between the Riksdag and the King.[6]

events.description: American Revolutionary War: Battle of Blue Licks: The last major engagement of the war, almost ten months after the surrender of the British commander Charles Cornwallis following the Siege of Yorktown.
events.html: • 1782 – American Revolutionary War: Battle of Blue Licks: The last major engagement of the war, almost ten months after the surrender of the British commander Charles Cornwallis following the Siege of Yorktown.

events.description: War of 1812: American frigate USS Constitution defeats the British frigate HMS Guerriere off the coast of Nova Scotia, Canada earning the nickname "Old Ironsides".
events.html: • 1812 – War of 1812: American frigate USS Constitution defeats the British frigate HMS Guerriere off the coast of Nova Scotia, Canada earning the nickname "Old Ironsides".

events.description: Gervasio Antonio de Posadas joins Argentina's Second Triumvirate.
events.html: • 1813 – Gervasio Antonio de Posadas joins Argentina's Second Triumvirate.

events.description: The French government announces that Louis Daguerre's photographic process is a gift "free to the world".
events.html: • 1839 – The French government announces that Louis Daguerre's photographic process is a gift "free to the world".

events.description: California Gold Rush: The New York Herald breaks the news to the East Coast of the United States of the gold rush in California (although the rush started in January).
events.html: • 1848 – California Gold Rush: The New York Herald breaks the news to the East Coast of the United States of the gold rush in California (although the rush started in January).

entities.name: East Coast of the United States

events.description: The First Sioux War begins when United States Army soldiers kill Lakota chief Conquering Bear and in return are massacred.
events.html: • 1854 – The First Sioux War begins when United States Army soldiers kill Lakota chief Conquering Bear and in return are massacred.

events.description: First ascent of Weisshorn, fifth highest summit in the Alps.
events.html: • 1861 – First ascent of Weisshorn, fifth highest summit in the Alps.

events.description: Dakota War: During an uprising in Minnesota, Lakota warriors decide not to attack heavily defended Fort Ridgely and instead turn to the settlement of New Ulm, killing white settlers along the way.
events.html: • 1862 – Dakota War: During an uprising in Minnesota, Lakota warriors decide not to attack heavily defended Fort Ridgely and instead turn to the settlement of New Ulm, killing white settlers along the way.

events.description: The Transfiguration Uprising breaks out in East Thrace, resulting in the establishment of the Strandzha Commune.
events.html: • 1903 – The Transfiguration Uprising breaks out in East Thrace, resulting in the establishment of the Strandzha Commune.[7]

events.description: The Indianapolis Motor Speedway opens for automobile racing. William Bourque and his mechanic are killed during the first day's events.
events.html: • 1909 – The Indianapolis Motor Speedway opens for automobile racing. William Bourque and his mechanic are killed during the first day's events.[8]

events.description: The Tambov Rebellion breaks out, in response to the Bolshevik policy of Prodrazvyorstka.
events.html: • 1920 – The Tambov Rebellion breaks out, in response to the Bolshevik policy of Prodrazvyorstka.[9]

events.description: Patriarch Sergius of Moscow proclaims the declaration of loyalty of the Russian Orthodox Church to the Soviet Union.
events.html: • 1927 – Patriarch Sergius of Moscow proclaims the declaration of loyalty of the Russian Orthodox Church to the Soviet Union.

events.description: The first All-American Soap Box Derby is held in Dayton, Ohio.
events.html: • 1934 – The first All-American Soap Box Derby is held in Dayton, Ohio.

events.description: The German referendum of 1934 approves Adolf Hitler's appointment as head of state with the title of Führer.
events.html: • 1934 – The German referendum of 1934 approves Adolf Hitler's appointment as head of state with the title of Führer.

events.description: The Great Purge of the Soviet Union begins when the first of the Moscow Trials is convened.
events.html: • 1936 – The Great Purge of the Soviet Union begins when the first of the Moscow Trials is convened.

events.description: First flight of the B-25 Mitchell medium bomber.
events.html: • 1940 – First flight of the B-25 Mitchell medium bomber.

events.description: Germany and Romania sign the Tiraspol Agreement, rendering the region of Transnistria under control of the latter.
events.html: • 1941 – Germany and Romania sign the Tiraspol Agreement, rendering the region of Transnistria under control of the latter.[10]

events.description: World War II: Operation Jubilee (The Dieppe Raid): The 2nd Canadian Infantry Division leads an amphibious assault by allied forces on Dieppe, France and fails.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Operation Jubilee (The Dieppe Raid): The 2nd Canadian Infantry Division leads an amphibious assault by allied forces on Dieppe, France and fails.

events.description: World War II: Liberation of Paris: Paris, France rises against German occupation with the help of Allied troops.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: Liberation of Paris: Paris, France rises against German occupation with the help of Allied troops.

events.description: August Revolution: Viet Minh led by Ho Chi Minh take power in Hanoi, Vietnam.
events.html: • 1945 – August Revolution: Viet Minh led by Ho Chi Minh take power in Hanoi, Vietnam.

events.description: Cold War: The CIA and MI6 help to overthrow the government of Mohammad Mosaddegh in Iran and reinstate the Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
events.html: • 1953 – Cold War: The CIA and MI6 help to overthrow the government of Mohammad Mosaddegh in Iran and reinstate the Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.

events.description: In the Northeast United States, severe flooding caused by Hurricane Diane, claims 200 lives.
events.html: • 1955 – In the Northeast United States, severe flooding caused by Hurricane Diane, claims 200 lives.

events.description: Cold War: In Moscow, Russia, Soviet Union, downed American U-2 pilot Francis Gary Powers is sentenced to ten years imprisonment by the Soviet Union for espionage.
events.html: • 1960 – Cold War: In Moscow, Russia, Soviet Union, downed American U-2 pilot Francis Gary Powers is sentenced to ten years imprisonment by the Soviet Union for espionage.

events.description: Sputnik program: Korabl-Sputnik 2: The Soviet Union launches the satellite with the dogs Belka and Strelka, 40 mice, two rats and a variety of plants.
events.html: • 1960 – Sputnik program: Korabl-Sputnik 2: The Soviet Union launches the satellite with the dogs Belka and Strelka, 40 mice, two rats and a variety of plants.

events.description: Syncom 3, the first geostationary communication satellite, is launched. Two months later, it would enable live coverage of the 1964 Summer Olympics.
events.html: • 1964 – Syncom 3, the first geostationary communication satellite, is launched. Two months later, it would enable live coverage of the 1964 Summer Olympics.

events.description: Japanese prime minister Eisaku Satō becomes the first post-World War II sitting prime minister to visit Okinawa Prefecture.
events.html: • 1965 – Japanese prime minister Eisaku Satō becomes the first post-World War II sitting prime minister to visit Okinawa Prefecture.

events.description: In Iran, the Cinema Rex fire causes more than 400 deaths.
events.html: • 1978 – In Iran, the Cinema Rex fire causes more than 400 deaths.

events.description: Saudia Flight 163, a Lockheed L-1011 TriStar burns after making an emergency landing at Riyadh International Airport in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, killing 301 people.
events.html: • 1980 – Saudia Flight 163, a Lockheed L-1011 TriStar burns after making an emergency landing at Riyadh International Airport in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, killing 301 people.

events.description: Otłoczyn railway accident: In Poland's worst post-war railway accident, 67 people lose their lives and a further 62 are injured.
events.html: • 1980 – Otłoczyn railway accident: In Poland's worst post-war railway accident, 67 people lose their lives and a further 62 are injured.[11]

events.description: Gulf of Sidra Incident: United States F-14A Tomcat fighters intercept and shoot down two Libyan Sukhoi Su-22 fighter jets over the Gulf of Sidra.
events.html: • 1981 – Gulf of Sidra Incident: United States F-14A Tomcat fighters intercept and shoot down two Libyan Sukhoi Su-22 fighter jets over the Gulf of Sidra.

events.description: Hungerford massacre: In the United Kingdom, Michael Ryan kills sixteen people with a semi-automatic rifle and then commits suicide.
events.html: • 1987 – Hungerford massacre: In the United Kingdom, Michael Ryan kills sixteen people with a semi-automatic rifle and then commits suicide.

events.description: Polish president Wojciech Jaruzelski nominates Solidarity activist Tadeusz Mazowiecki to be the first non-communist prime minister in 42 years.
events.html: • 1989 – Polish president Wojciech Jaruzelski nominates Solidarity activist Tadeusz Mazowiecki to be the first non-communist prime minister in 42 years.

events.description: Several hundred East Germans cross the frontier between Hungary and Austria during the Pan-European Picnic, part of the events that began the process of the Fall of the Berlin Wall.
events.html: • 1989 – Several hundred East Germans cross the frontier between Hungary and Austria during the Pan-European Picnic, part of the events that began the process of the Fall of the Berlin Wall.

events.description: Dissolution of the Soviet Union: The August Coup begins when Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev is placed under house arrest while on holiday in the town of Foros, Ukraine.
events.html: • 1991 – Dissolution of the Soviet Union: The August Coup begins when Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev is placed under house arrest while on holiday in the town of Foros, Ukraine.

events.description: Crown Heights riot begins.
events.html: • 1991 – Crown Heights riot begins.[12]

events.description: In Belgrade, Yugoslavia, tens of thousands of Serbians rally to demand the resignation of Federal Republic of Yugoslavia President Slobodan Milošević.
events.html: • 1999 – In Belgrade, Yugoslavia, tens of thousands of Serbians rally to demand the resignation of Federal Republic of Yugoslavia President Slobodan Milošević.

events.description: Khankala Mi-26 crash: A Russian Mil Mi-26 helicopter carrying troops is hit by a Chechen missile outside Grozny, killing 118 soldiers.
events.html: • 2002 – Khankala Mi-26 crash: A Russian Mil Mi-26 helicopter carrying troops is hit by a Chechen missile outside Grozny, killing 118 soldiers.

events.description: A truck-bomb attack on United Nations headquarters in Iraq kills the agency's top envoy Sérgio Vieira de Mello and 21 other employees.
events.html: • 2003 – A truck-bomb attack on United Nations headquarters in Iraq kills the agency's top envoy Sérgio Vieira de Mello and 21 other employees.[13]

events.description: Shmuel HaNavi bus bombing: A suicide attack on a bus in Jerusalem, planned by Hamas, kills 23 Israelis, seven of them children.
events.html: • 2003 – Shmuel HaNavi bus bombing: A suicide attack on a bus in Jerusalem, planned by Hamas, kills 23 Israelis, seven of them children.[14]

events.description: Google Inc. has its initial public offering on Nasdaq.
events.html: • 2004 – Google Inc. has its initial public offering on Nasdaq.[15]

events.description: The first-ever joint military exercise between Russia and China, called Peace Mission 2005 begins.
events.html: • 2005 – The first-ever joint military exercise between Russia and China, called Peace Mission 2005 begins.

events.description: A series of bombings in Baghdad, Iraq, kills 101 and injures 565 others.
events.html: • 2009 – A series of bombings in Baghdad, Iraq, kills 101 and injures 565 others.

events.description: Operation Iraqi Freedom ends, with the last of the United States brigade combat teams crossing the border to Kuwait.
events.html: • 2010 – Operation Iraqi Freedom ends, with the last of the United States brigade combat teams crossing the border to Kuwait.

events.description: The Dhamara Ghat train accident kills at least 37 people in the Indian state of Bihar.
events.html: • 2013 – The Dhamara Ghat train accident kills at least 37 people in the Indian state of Bihar.

events.description: Tens of thousands of farmed non-native Atlantic salmon are accidentally released into the wild in Washington waters in the 2017 Cypress Island Atlantic salmon pen break.
events.html: • 2017 – Tens of thousands of farmed non-native Atlantic salmon are accidentally released into the wild in Washington waters in the 2017 Cypress Island Atlantic salmon pen break.

entities.name: Cypress Island Atlantic salmon pen break
